                        <h3 class="mbr-section-title mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-2">
                            <strong>Understanding Euler’s Formula</h3></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Leonhard Euler is commonly regarded, and rightfully so, as one of greatest mathematicians of all time. The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_things_named_after_Leonhard_Euler" target="_self">list</a> of theorems, equations, constants, etc. named after him is unmatched. There are so many mathematical topics named after him that if I were refer to Euler’s formula, I would have to specify <em>which one</em>. For now let’s consider one particular identity of his*, namely:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
