0w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*b8_PNj6EiB4LNr4tTTIVDw.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*b8_PNj6EiB4LNr4tTTIVDw.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*b8_PNj6EiB4LNr4tTTIVDw.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:800/1*b8_PNj6EiB4LNr4tTTIVDw.png 800w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:400/1*b8_PNj6EiB4LNr4tTTIVDw.png"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">A usual response to Euler’s identity. (Relevant xkcd)</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Veteran mathematicians and fledgling calculus students alike gawk at Euler’s identity. It has been described as “the most beautiful equation in mathematics,” and for good reason. It relates the 5 most fundamental constants of mathematics:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><ul><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">π — pi</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><em>e</em> — Euler’s number</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><em>i — </em>Imaginary Unit (Square root of -1)</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">1 — One (Unity)</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">0 — Zero (Nothing)</li></ul></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">While this equation is certainly <em>beautiful</em>, or at least <em>significant</em>, it is only one case of a more general formula:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:65%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 487px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*JkPmdRLM31EcMmbIQ8EgVA.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*JkPmdRLM31EcMmbIQ8EgVA.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*JkPmdRLM31EcMmbIQ8EgVA.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*JkPmdRLM31EcMmbIQ8EgVA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*JkPmdRLM31EcMmbIQ8EgVA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*JkPmdRLM31EcMmbIQ8EgVA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:974/format:webp/1*JkPmdRLM31EcMmbIQ8EgVA.png 974w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 487px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*JkPmdRLM31EcMmbIQ8EgVA.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*JkPmdRLM31EcMmbIQ8EgVA.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*JkPmdRLM31EcMmbIQ8EgVA.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*JkPmdRLM31EcMmbIQ8EgVA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*JkPmdRLM31EcMmbIQ8EgVA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*JkPmdRLM31EcMmbIQ8EgVA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:974/1*JkPmdRLM31EcMmbIQ8EgVA.png 974w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:487/1*JkPmdRLM31EcMmbIQ8EgVA.png"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">Euler’s formula</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">To me, this is much more interesting than Euler’s identity. It manages to relate exponentiation, complex exponentiation in fact, to the trigonometric functions. And as a result, this equation serves as a bridge between several topics relating to complex numbers including: complex logarithms, complex numbers in polar form, complex/imaginary angles, and so on. I go into more detail on the application of Euler's formula in <a href="https://medium.com/@ozanerhansha/applications-of-eulers-formula-857bf60ba32d" target="_self">another post</a>.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">But how does one arrive at such a magnificent (if not a bit intimidating) formula? What does a number to the power of an imaginary number even mean? Can we really say these two expressions <em>equal</em> each other?</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">In this article I will attempt to show how to get to Euler’s formula assuming you know three things:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><ul><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">What an <strong>imaginary number</strong> is (<em>i </em>= <strong>√</strong>-1)</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">A very basic idea of <strong>differentiation</strong>, i.e. you know what a <strong>derivative</strong> is (this is really all the calculus you’ll need).</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">And what a <strong>factorial</strong> is, e.g. 5 factorial is written as 5! and equals 5*4*3*2*1=120.</li></ul></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">There are a few sub-points, or <strong>lemmas</strong>, to explain before we finally put them all together and prove Euler’s Formula. If you already happen to know a certain lemma then you can of course skip over it.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-7">Lemma 1: The Powers of i are Cyclical</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The first important fact we must establish is that as you raise <em>i</em> to the 0th, 1st, 2nd, 3rd, and so on powers, a pattern starts to emerge:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:52%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 397px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*rXBLX2oGMPW53f-YymZQAA.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*rXBLX2oGMPW53f-YymZQAA.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*rXBLX2oGMPW53f-YymZQAA.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*rXBLX2oGMPW53f-YymZQAA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*rXBLX2oGMPW53f-YymZQAA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*rXBLX2oGMPW53f-YymZQAA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:794/format:webp/1*rXBLX2oGMPW53f-YymZQAA.png 794w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 397px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*rXBLX2oGMPW53f-YymZQAA.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*rXBLX2oGMPW53f-YymZQAA.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*rXBLX2oGMPW53f-YymZQAA.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*rXBLX2oGMPW53f-YymZQAA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*rXBLX2oGMPW53f-YymZQAA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*rXBLX2oGMPW53f-YymZQAA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:794/1*rXBLX2oGMPW53f-YymZQAA.png 794w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:397/1*rXBLX2oGMPW53f-YymZQAA.png"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">The powers of i from 0 to 7</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">As you can see the powers repeat, or <strong>cycle</strong>, every 4th number. This makes calculating an arbitrary integer power of <em>i</em> simple.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">To find <em>i</em>ⁿ, just divide n by 4 and look at the remainder. If the remainder is:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><ul><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">0 then <em>i</em>ⁿ = 1</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">1 then <em>i</em>ⁿ = <em>i</em></li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">2 then <em>i</em>ⁿ = -1</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">3 then <em>i</em>ⁿ = -<em>i</em></li></ul></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Put another way:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:35%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 273px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*K0KqFnFWTYrJW7hJ5muU-g.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*K0KqFnFWTYrJW7hJ5muU-g.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*K0KqFnFWTYrJW7hJ5muU-g.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*K0KqFnFWTYrJW7hJ5muU-g.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*K0KqFnFWTYrJW7hJ5muU-g.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*K0KqFnFWTYrJW7hJ5muU-g.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:546/format:webp/1*K0KqFnFWTYrJW7hJ5muU-g.png 546w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 273px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*K0KqFnFWTYrJW7hJ5muU-g.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*K0KqFnFWTYrJW7hJ5muU-g.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*K0KqFnFWTYrJW7hJ5muU-g.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*K0KqFnFWTYrJW7hJ5muU-g.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*K0KqFnFWTYrJW7hJ5muU-g.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*K0KqFnFWTYrJW7hJ5muU-g.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:546/1*K0KqFnFWTYrJW7hJ5muU-g.png 546w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:273/1*K0KqFnFWTYrJW7hJ5muU-g.png"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">For any integer n <strong>[lemma 1]</strong></p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Where (<em>n</em> mod 4) means the remainder after n has been divided by 4. Keep in mind that this is only true when <em>n</em> is an integer (…-3,-2,-1,0,1,2,3…) and not if it is a fractional or irrational number (3/5, π, <strong>√</strong>2, etc).</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><em>**If it’s unclear why the powers of i do this, keep in mind that:</em></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><ul><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><em>Any number to the power of 0 is 1,</em></li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><em>Any number to the power of 1 is that same number,</em></li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><em>And i² is -1 because the definition of i is that it is </em><strong>√</strong><em>-1.</em></li></ul></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><em>Once you know these three things the higher powers are just repeated multiplication of i.</em></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-7">Lemma 2: The Derivatives of Sine & Cosine</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The second piece of proving Euler’s formula is knowing the derivative of the sine and cosine functions:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*H-YJ9qySviblTjNLh7isuA.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*H-YJ9qySviblTjNLh7isuA.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*H-YJ9qySviblTjNLh7isuA.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*H-YJ9qySviblTjNLh7isuA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*H-YJ9qySviblTjNLh7isuA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*H-YJ9qySviblTjNLh7isuA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*H-YJ9qySviblTjNLh7isuA.png 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*H-YJ9qySviblTjNLh7isuA.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*H-YJ9qySviblTjNLh7isuA.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*H-YJ9qySviblTjNLh7isuA.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*H-YJ9qySviblTjNLh7isuA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*H-YJ9qySviblTjNLh7isuA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*H-YJ9qySviblTjNLh7isuA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*H-YJ9qySviblTjNLh7isuA.png 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:700/1*H-YJ9qySviblTjNLh7isuA.png"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">The derivatives of Sine and Cosine are cyclical <strong>[lemma 2]</strong></p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">If you want a calculus level proof of the derivatives of <a href="https://www.wyzant.com/resources/lessons/math/calculus/derivative_proofs/sinx" target="_self">sine</a> and <a href="https://www.wyzant.com/resources/lessons/math/calculus/derivative_proofs/cosx" target="_self">cosine</a> (which uses the formal definition of a derivative) refer to the linked webpages. They are short and make use of trigonometric identities.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:43%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 332px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*cTHQt7q6Gg2QdTGOLWrSow.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*cTHQt7q6Gg2QdTGOLWrSow.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*cTHQt7q6Gg2QdTGOLWrSow.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*cTHQt7q6Gg2QdTGOLWrSow.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*cTHQt7q6Gg2QdTGOLWrSow.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*cTHQt7q6Gg2QdTGOLWrSow.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:664/format:webp/1*cTHQt7q6Gg2QdTGOLWrSow.png 664w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 332px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*cTHQt7q6Gg2QdTGOLWrSow.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*cTHQt7q6Gg2QdTGOLWrSow.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*cTHQt7q6Gg2QdTGOLWrSow.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*cTHQt7q6Gg2QdTGOLWrSow.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*cTHQt7q6Gg2QdTGOLWrSow.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*cTHQt7q6Gg2QdTGOLWrSow.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:664/1*cTHQt7q6Gg2QdTGOLWrSow.png 664w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:332/1*cTHQt7q6Gg2QdTGOLWrSow.png"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">The derivative of -f(x) is the negative of the derivative of f(x) (i.e. you can ‘pull out’ the negative sign from inside the derivative.)</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">If we accept the derivatives of <em>sin x</em> and <em>cos x</em> we can quickly see that the derivatives of <em>-sin x</em> and <em>-cos x</em> are the same but multiplied by -1.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Notice how the pattern the derivatives make is similar to the pattern the powers of <em>i</em> make. Every 4th derivative the functions cycle back. So to find the <em>n</em>th derivative of <em>sin x</em>, simply calculate <em>n</em> mod 4. If the remainder is:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><ul><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">0 then the <em>n</em>th derivative is <em>sin x</em></li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">1 then the <em>n</em>th derivative is <em>cos x</em></li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">2 then the <em>n</em>th derivative is <em>-sin x</em></li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">3 then the <em>n</em>th derivative is <em>-cos x</em></li></ul></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The derivatives of cosine are calculated in much the same way.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Another thing to note is that we can keep differentiating <em>sin x</em> and <em>cos x </em>as much as we want. A function with this property is called <strong>infinitely differentiable</strong>.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-7">Lemma 3: The Derivative of the Exponential Function</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Another interesting derivative we must keep in mind is that of the exponential function. The exponential function is <em>eˣ </em>where <em>e</em> is <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E_(mathematical_constant)" target="_self">Euler's number</a>. What’s special about this function is that it is the unique function whose derivative is itself:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:26%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 212px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*6EjUct_x2oP2edjUH3f_7Q.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*6EjUct_x2oP2edjUH3f_7Q.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*6EjUct_x2oP2edjUH3f_7Q.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*6EjUct_x2oP2edjUH3f_7Q.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*6EjUct_x2oP2edjUH3f_7Q.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*6EjUct_x2oP2edjUH3f_7Q.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:424/format:webp/1*6EjUct_x2oP2edjUH3f_7Q.png 424w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 212px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*6EjUct_x2oP2edjUH3f_7Q.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*6EjUct_x2oP2edjUH3f_7Q.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*6EjUct_x2oP2edjUH3f_7Q.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*6EjUct_x2oP2edjUH3f_7Q.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*6EjUct_x2oP2edjUH3f_7Q.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*6EjUct_x2oP2edjUH3f_7Q.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:424/1*6EjUct_x2oP2edjUH3f_7Q.png 424w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:212/1*6EjUct_x2oP2edjUH3f_7Q.png"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">The derivative of <em>e</em>ˣ is itself. <strong>[lemma 3]</strong></p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">As with sine and cosine, a formal proof of this can be found <a href="https://www.wyzant.com/resources/lessons/math/calculus/derivative_proofs/e_to_the_x" target="_self">here</a>.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><em>Note: Some mathematicians define the exponential function as the unique function whose derivative is itself. In this case a proof is unnecessary as the very definition of the function is what we are trying to prove.</em></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The exponential function being its own derivative has a variety consequences which make this function interesting to study, but what we are mainly interested in right now is that this function is, like sine and cosine, <strong>infinitely differentiable</strong>. No matter how many times you differentiate <em>eˣ</em> you always get back <em>eˣ,</em> i.e. the <em>n</em>th derivative of <em>eˣ</em> is <em>eˣ</em>.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-7">Lemma 4: Taylor & <strong>Maclaurin </strong>Series’</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">This lemma is probably the most interesting of them all, and is what allows us to connect the exponential function and the two trigonometric functions later down the line.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">In 1712 English mathematician <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brook_Taylor" target="_self">Brook Taylor</a> came up with an ingenious way to estimate any differentiable function as a polynomial:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*w6_URF-NbLv1JOEN9ts50Q.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*w6_URF-NbLv1JOEN9ts50Q.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*w6_URF-NbLv1JOEN9ts50Q.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*w6_URF-NbLv1JOEN9ts50Q.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*w6_URF-NbLv1JOEN9ts50Q.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*w6_URF-NbLv1JOEN9ts50Q.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*w6_URF-NbLv1JOEN9ts50Q.png 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*w6_URF-NbLv1JOEN9ts50Q.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*w6_URF-NbLv1JOEN9ts50Q.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*w6_URF-NbLv1JOEN9ts50Q.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*w6_URF-NbLv1JOEN9ts50Q.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*w6_URF-NbLv1JOEN9ts50Q.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*w6_URF-NbLv1JOEN9ts50Q.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*w6_URF-NbLv1JOEN9ts50Q.png 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:700/1*w6_URF-NbLv1JOEN9ts50Q.png"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">An nth degree Taylor Polynomial</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">This may seem complicated but lets break it down.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><ul><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><em>f(x)</em> is the function we are approximating,</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><em>n</em> is the degree of our polynomial.</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><em>a</em> is the value we are centering our approximation on. In the formula we are to take repeated derivatives of <em>f(x)</em> at the value <em>a</em> for each new term.</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">the superscripts on <em>f</em> denote what derivative we are talking about. <em>f’</em> is the 1st derivative, <em>f’’</em> the 2nd derivative, and <em>fⁿ</em> the nth derivative.</li></ul></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The larger the <em>n</em> we choose, the more accurate our estimate. However keep in mind not all functions are infinitely differentiable (for some there is a limit to how many times you can differentiate them) so some functions can only approximated to a maximum <em>n</em> value.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*GJ5O9OhqydbEMUlKk3czYw.gif 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*GJ5O9OhqydbEMUlKk3czYw.gif 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*GJ5O9OhqydbEMUlKk3czYw.gif 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*GJ5O9OhqydbEMUlKk3czYw.gif 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*GJ5O9OhqydbEMUlKk3czYw.gif 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*GJ5O9OhqydbEMUlKk3czYw.gif 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*GJ5O9OhqydbEMUlKk3czYw.gif 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*GJ5O9OhqydbEMUlKk3czYw.gif 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*GJ5O9OhqydbEMUlKk3czYw.gif 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*GJ5O9OhqydbEMUlKk3czYw.gif 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*GJ5O9OhqydbEMUlKk3czYw.gif 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*GJ5O9OhqydbEMUlKk3czYw.gif 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*GJ5O9OhqydbEMUlKk3czYw.gif 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*GJ5O9OhqydbEMUlKk3czYw.gif 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:700/1*GJ5O9OhqydbEMUlKk3czYw.gif"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">In the example above, we are approximating the <em>sin x</em> function with 0 as its center (<em>a=</em>0), and with <em>n=</em>15. So this is a 15th degree <strong>Taylor polynomial</strong>.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Notice that the more terms we add (i.e. the bigger <em>n</em> is) the more the approximation looks like the actual function around the value <em>a</em>. So, one might think “What if we let <em>n=∞</em>?” Wouldn’t that infinite polynomial, or <strong>series</strong>, actually <em>equal </em>the function rather than approximate it? In 1715 <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Gregory_(mathematician)" target="_self">James Gregory</a> thought just that and proved that yes, it is valid to say that a function would actually equal this infinite polynomial*. Such an infinite polynomial is called a <strong>Taylor series</strong>.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><em>*not all functions are equal to their Taylor series, but we can prove that the exponential, sine, and cosine functions are.</em></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Before I show you the expression for this Taylor series, I would like to make one more point. Remember how we had some center point <em>a</em>, in which the approximation was focused around? Well if we are allowing <em>n</em> to go infinity it doesn’t matter what the center point is. As such we can set <em>a=</em>0 to make the expression simpler. If we do set <em>a=</em>0 then the resulting Taylor series is called a <strong>Maclaurin series</strong>:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*FklKQafTJy-daXH8Fs3DeA.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*FklKQafTJy-daXH8Fs3DeA.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*FklKQafTJy-daXH8Fs3DeA.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*FklKQafTJy-daXH8Fs3DeA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*FklKQafTJy-daXH8Fs3DeA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*FklKQafTJy-daXH8Fs3DeA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*FklKQafTJy-daXH8Fs3DeA.png 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*FklKQafTJy-daXH8Fs3DeA.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*FklKQafTJy-daXH8Fs3DeA.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*FklKQafTJy-daXH8Fs3DeA.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*FklKQafTJy-daXH8Fs3DeA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*FklKQafTJy-daXH8Fs3DeA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*FklKQafTJy-daXH8Fs3DeA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*FklKQafTJy-daXH8Fs3DeA.png 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:700/1*FklKQafTJy-daXH8Fs3DeA.png"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">The Maclaurin series for a function f(x) <strong>[lemma 4]</strong></p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">This is a lot simpler than our original function for a Taylor polynomial and a lot more powerful as well. We can now turn an <strong>infinitely differentiable</strong> function (because this is an infinite polynomial where each term needs a higher derivative then the last) into an infinite polynomial expansion. This is a profound equation on its own, but we are going to go further and use it to derive Euler’s formula.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-7">Lemma 5: The Maclaurin Series for the Exponential Function</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Let’s apply our newfound knowledge of Maclaurin series’ to the exponential function, which we already know is infinitely differentiable:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
